\begin_layout Section
Flashlight geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The introduction proposes a priviledged point, the astronaut, surrounded
 by a spherical shell of infalling flashlights.
 For practical calculations, it is more convenient to visualize the astronaut
 as being surrounded by a cloud, a uniformly distributed dust of flashlights.
 The goal of this section is to describe the infalling geodesics of the
 astronaut and these flashlights.
 Since these are meant to be radially infalling, this should be easy.
 To make the notation unambiguous, some preliminaries need to be cleared
 up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Conceptual framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This dust of flashlights should be thought of as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart dust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, so that each flashlight is a computer, capable of carrying a universally
 unique id (UUID) that identifies it.
 When each flashlight broadcasts, it should be thought of as a GPS transmitter,
 so that the transmission encodes the UUID number.
 This does not alter the mathematical description of the geodesics in any
 way; instead, the goal here is that each geodesic can be given a unique,
 unambiguous label, about which there can be no confusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, when a flashlight broadcasts, it can also encode the direction
 in which it is broadcasting the signal.
 That is, each flashlight carries an intertial frame (say, by gyroscopes
 built into it), and when the flashlight transmits a narrow beam in some
 given direction, it can encode that direction into the beam itself.
 Recall the engineering of this: it can be done with pseudorandom bit sequences.
 The flashlight modulates the transmission with this directional information
 (using AM, FM, SSB, PCM, quadrature; any conventional radio technique will
 work.) Again, this changes nothing, other than reinforcing the idea that
 each null geodesic emanating from the flashlight can be uniquely identified
 with the initial direction in which it was emitted.
 The flashlight can also carry a clock, measuring the proper time for that
 flashlight, and this time can also be encoded into the transmission.
 Thus, for each null geodesic, it can be accurately labelled with a timestamp
 indicating the proper time when it was emitted.
 Note finally that each radio transmission can also be polarized, thus indicatin
g the remaining degree of freedom in the positioning of the transmitter.
 That is, radio waves can completely encode information about the transmitter
 at the time of the transmission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flashlight
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used, implying light or radio emissions propagating along null geodesics,
 these flashlights could equally be machine rifles, shooting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart bullets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this case, each bullet could be a computer.
 This computer can carry information about which gun it was shot from, and
 when, and what direction (so, the same as the radio transmissions), but
 also the velocity.
 Each bullet can be equipped with a clock, and with gyroscopes, so that,
 again, there is no doubt whatsoever is to it's inertial frame.
 Each bullet is also capable of acting as a radio receiver, and recording
 a history of those receptions; bullets have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

memory of the past
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Upon reception of the bullet by the observer (the falling astronaut), this
 information can be queried and analyzed by the astronaut.
 Again, this does not change any of the algebra used to describe the geodesics;
 it does, however, sharpen the the kind of information that can be attached
 to the timelike geodesics emitted by the flashlight-guns.
 Also worth keeping in mind that the null geodesics cannot carry this kind
 of information.
 The null geodesic cannot 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remember
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 what it saw along the way; the null geodesic has no proper time, no recording
 mechanism, no memory, no subjective, experienced history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Flashlight labels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed to label the flashlights.
 Starting at a location 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2m$
\end_inset

, where spacetime is approximately flat, we establish an inertial frame.
 This frame can be labelled with either orthonormal coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 or with polar coordinates.
 The labelling is done at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

, and we set the proper time to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 for all flashlights.
 There is no engineering or mathematical challenge to arranging this.
 Its all standard lab technique.
 Place the astronaut at the origin, the privileged point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=z=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For polar coordinates, the following notation is used: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With respect to the Schwarschild coordinates, the astronaut is initially
 located at at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}\gg2m$
\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 in the Schwarschild chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}$
\end_inset

 be the radial location of a flashlight with respect to the astronaut.
 This number should be thought of as a UUID, a constant that never changes.
 It is stored in the flashlight computer memory itself, and does not change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general, we'll wish to keep the cloud of flashlights relatively small,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\ll r_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a valid assumption.
 It seems like this could be a useful simplifying assumption, at some point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The flashlights are meant to be uniformly distributed, so that we can meaningful
ly talk about a Euclidean measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 describing the local density of the flashlights.
 We will want to track the time evolution of this measure, although this
 might prove to be a challenging task.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let the polar coordinates of a flashlight be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\alpha\le\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi\le\beta\le\pi$
\end_inset

.
 These are the altitude and azimuth, respectively.
 The convention is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 is the zenith, pointing towards the black hole.
 The azimuth 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 must be specified with respect to the celestial meridian.
 It is aligned so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 (That is, each flashlight will be located at some 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\ne0$
\end_inset

 and therefore at some generally non-zero 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to place the meridian 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

 at the same place where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.) Let the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 be reserved for the third Euler angle, which will be needed to determine
 the flashlight polarization.
 It will be defined later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These angular coordinates are meant only to uniquely identify each flashlight.
 Again, they are a UUID assigned to each flashlight.
 This UUID number does not change over time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orthonormal coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 for the lab frame (body frame) are related in the standard way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =R\sin\alpha\cos\beta\\
y & =R\sin\alpha\sin\beta\\
z & =R\cos\alpha
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Positive 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 points towards the black hole, it corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 Positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

.
 The coordinates are right-handed, so that positive 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

