name "Radial Infall Lecture 31 Physics 411 Classical Mechanics II 14 November 2007 Reed College"
target "https://www.reed.edu/physics/courses/Physics411/html/411/page2/files/Lecture.31.pdf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Its slightly more verbose in some places, and more compact in others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian for a massive particle following a time-like trajectory is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}\dot{x}^{\mu}\dot{x}^{\nu}
\]

\end_inset

where the shorthand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}^{\mu}=\frac{dx^{\mu}}{d\tau}
\]

\end_inset

is used.
 It's also handy to recall the Legendre transform.
 Defining the conjugate momentum as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\mu}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}^{\mu}}
\]

\end_inset

the Hamiltonian is then 
\begin_inset Formula $H=p_{\mu}\dot{x}^{\mu}-L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Schwarzschild chart, it is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}^{2}-\frac{\dot{r}^{2}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}-r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}-r^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

For radial infall, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}=\dot{\phi}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The Euler-Lagrange equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}^{\mu}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial x^{\mu}}=0
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}=t$
\end_inset

 one obviously has 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial L/\partial t=0$
\end_inset

 and so one has a constant of motion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{const}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{t}}
\]

\end_inset

Call this the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Working this out explicitly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{const}=\frac{E}{m}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{t}}=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}
\]

\end_inset

This is writen so that the constant is dimensionless, and the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has the same units as the mass.
 This eqn is the same as the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}=r$
\end_inset

, the radial equation is brute-forced:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=\frac{m}{r^{2}}\dot{t}^{2}+\frac{\dot{r}^{2}}{\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\frac{m}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Plugging in for the energy,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=\frac{m}{r^{2}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\left(\dot{r}^{2}+\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The momentum is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{r}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}=-\frac{\dot{r}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}=-\frac{\ddot{r}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}+\frac{\dot{r}^{2}}{\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\frac{2m}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=-\frac{\ddot{r}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}+\frac{m}{r^{2}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\left(\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}\ddot{r}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)=m\left(\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is the same as the earlier eqn.
 So we got the same equation two different ways.
 Hurrah! I think it's correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Newtonian limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can plug in for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{t}$
\end_inset

 in the Lagrangian to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}\left(\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}-\dot{r}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Inserting this into the geodesic equation gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}\ddot{r}=-2mL
\]

\end_inset

This can be directly compared to the Newtonian limit.
 This would be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{r}=-\frac{Gm}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 was inserted explicitly, just to jog the memory.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

 in our units.
 From this, one may conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1/2$
\end_inset

 for massive particles falling in the radial direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There's a second case, obtained by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}=\pm\frac{E}{m}
\]

\end_inset

solves the geodesic equation, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through, one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since the Lagrangian was explicitly constructed from the metric, one concludes
 that these are null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Physical interpretation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why can 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be taken to be a constant along geodesics? Well, geodesics minimize arc
 length; this is the same as minimizing the energy, or minimizing the action.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $H=L$
\end_inset

 for the Schwarschild metric, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian obtained from the Legendre transform above.
 Writing the total (square of the) arc length as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int Ld\tau
\]

\end_inset

it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mbox{const}$
\end_inset

 minimizes this.
 The shortest line between two points is a straight line; this remains the
 case, if one thinks of 
\begin_inset Formula $L\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 as a plain-old ordinary real function of a single real parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 There's nothing more to it.
 A more precise and convincing formulation is given in Jost
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jost2002geom"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, although Jost covers only the case for Riemannian manifolds.
 Close enough.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1/2$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a line element of unit length.
 That is, all time-like tangent vectors always have unit length.
 This is merely a formality.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is simply a real number that paramterizes distinct points along some arc
 (including, but not limited to geodesics.) As a parameter, one is free to
 reparmeterize 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\to c\tau+\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c\ne1$
\end_inset

 and constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 Such reparametrization does not change the arc itself.
 Thus, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

 does not alter the arc itself.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

speed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 along the arc; for spacetime, we call it the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

speed of light
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The paramter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proper time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the physics literature, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=t$
\end_inset

 in the free-falling frames.
 Thus, the parameterization of time-like geodesics to unit speed is merely
 an algebraic convenience, nothing more.
 Taking the Newtonian limit, as above, allows these arbitrary constants
 to be identified and given physical meaning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For null geodesics, there's a common confusion abut the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proper time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that should be noted.
 The radial geodesics with 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

 correspond to tangent vectors of zero length, according to the metric.
 This does not mean that that such tangent vectors cannot be integrated
 to obtain an arc.
 The paramter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is still a valid parameter for locating points along the arc.
 Indeed, the radial coordinate is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\dot{r}\tau$
\end_inset

 for the null geodesics.
 The only difficulty or confusion arises when the paramter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is conflated with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It is not, nor is it measuring the arc length of null geodesics (the arc
 length is zero!).
 Thus, we should call 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

arc parameter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proper time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 However, fighting tradition is hard, and this is not the battle for the
 moment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, one can reparameterize 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\to f\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 for some diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a reparameterization does not change the location of arcs on a fixed
 manifold.
 If one beleives that physics is described only by the location of such
 arcs, then one considers the space of all arcs, modulo all diffeomorphisms
 of arc paramterizations.
 Working in this quotient space is the standard convention in (psuedo-)Riemannia
n geometry, as doing otherwise seems to lead only to more complicated situations
 that offer no particular insight into the geometry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another point to keep in mind is that the quantum formulation requires consideri
ng all arcs, and not just the geodesics.
 The Lagrangian is no longer a constant, and one performs path integrals
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Feynmann integrals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) over all arcs, to obtain the partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 These arcs also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 as an arc parameter.
 This time, diffeomorphic reparameterizations 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\to f\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 cause the Lagrangian to change as 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L\dot{f}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For conventional QFT in curved spacetimes, I beleive that the intent is
 to use a measure for the path integrals that is invariant under such reparamete
rizations.
 I beleive that the intent of string theory is to allow such reparamterizations,
 and to give them dynamics.
 That is, string theory is not so much about little itty-bitty strings having
 some spatial extent, but rather, even for a fixed arc on a fixed manifold,
 one must consider such reparameterizations.
 That is, sometimes the two endpoints of an open string correspond to the
 same point on the arc, and sometimes to different points on the same arc,
 and sometimes to different points on different arcs.
 At least, I think that is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

intended
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interpretation of string theory, although I am quite sure there are thousands
 of people out there willing to shout at me about how wrong I am.
 Sigh.
 So it goes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above manipulations expose a constant of motion, 
\begin_inset Formula $E/m$
\end_inset

.
 The physical interpretation of this remains unclear.
 For the timelike geodesics, a simple solution can be obtained if 
\begin_inset Formula $E=m$
\end_inset

, but otherwise the equations look difficult to solve.
 Should I assume that the solutions for 
\begin_inset Formula $E\ne m$
\end_inset

 ar equivalent to those for 
\begin_inset Formula $E=m$
\end_inset

 after appropriate Lorentz transformations? If so, this is not obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the null geodesics, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}=\mbox{const}$
\end_inset

 it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $E/m$
\end_inset

 is nothing more than a linear reparametrization of the arc parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, and so one can set 
\begin_inset Formula $E=m$
\end_inset

 without any loss of generality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Timelike radial geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Presuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1/2$
\end_inset

 is a constant, the radial geodesic equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}\ddot{r}=-m$
\end_inset

.
 Reinserting this into the earlier form gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}^{2}=\frac{2m}{r}+\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}-1
\]

\end_inset

The same form can be found with the Ansatz
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{r}\ddot{r}= & \frac{1}{2}\frac{d}{d\tau}\dot{r}^{2}\\
= & -\frac{m\dot{r}}{r^{2}}\\
= & \frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{m}{r}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Integrating this gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}^{2}=\frac{2m}{r}+A
\]

\end_inset

with a constant of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $A=E^{2}/m^{2}-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest way to solve this is to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 and then invert, rather than trying to get to 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 directly.
 This is done by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\tau}{dr}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m+Ar}}
\]

\end_inset

For now, set 
\begin_inset Formula $A=0$
\end_inset

; the case for 
\begin_inset Formula $A\ne0$
\end_inset

 isn't currently examined.
 Integrating this directly gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\tau\left(r\right)=\tau_{0}\pm\frac{2}{3}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2m}}\left(r^{3/2}-r_{0}^{3/2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the initial position of flashlight 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at initial time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The infalling geodesic corresponds to the choice of the minus sign, so
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $r<r_{0}$
\end_inset

 results in increasing proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau>\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Inverting this gives the rather busy expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\left(\tau\right)=\left[r_{0}^{3/2}-\frac{3\sqrt{2m}}{2}\left(\tau-\tau_{0}\right)\right]^{2/3}
\]

\end_inset

Curiously, this expression is not singular at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2m$
\end_inset

.
 However, the integral providing the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 does exhibit a pole at that point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by direct integration.
 Starting from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{E}{m}=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}
\]

\end_inset

the time coordinate is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t\left(\tau\right)= & \frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{r\left(s\right)}{r\left(s\right)-2m}ds\\
= & \frac{E}{m}\left[\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}ds+2m\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{ds}{r\left(s\right)-2m}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hmm.
 We can try to brute-force the second integral, but that seems tedious.
 A change of variable seems to be easier.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\tau}{dr}=\frac{dt}{dr}\frac{d\tau}{dt}=-\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}
\]

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dt}{dr}=-\dot{t}\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}=-\frac{1}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E=m$
\end_inset

 is taken because that was already assumed for the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}$
\end_inset

 up above.
 Integrating, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\left(r\right)=-\int_{r_{0}}^{r}\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}\frac{1}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}dr
\]

\end_inset

Yuck.
 Change of variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sqrt{2m/r}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2m/x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dr=-4mdx/x^{3}$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-\int\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}\frac{1}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}dr= & 4m\int\frac{dx}{x^{4}\left(1-x^{2}\right)}\\
= & 4m\left[\int\frac{dx}{x^{4}}+\int\frac{dx}{x^{2}\left(1-x^{2}\right)}\right]\\
= & 4m\left[\int\frac{dx}{x^{4}}+\int\frac{dx}{x^{2}}+\int\frac{dx}{1-x^{2}}\right]\\
= & 4m\left[-\frac{1}{3x^{3}}-\frac{1}{x}-\frac{1}{2}\log\left|\frac{1-x}{1+x}\right|\right]\\
= & -4m\left[\frac{r}{6m}\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}+\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}+\frac{1}{2}\log\left|\frac{1-\sqrt{2m/r}}{1+\sqrt{2m/r}}\right|\right]\\
= & -\frac{2}{3}\left(r+6m\right)\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}-2m\log\left|\frac{1-\sqrt{2m/r}}{1+\sqrt{2m/r}}\right|
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is a bit tedious.
 Concluding, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\left(r\right)=\left.\frac{2}{3}\left(r+6m\right)\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}+2m\log\left|\frac{1-\sqrt{2m/r}}{1+\sqrt{2m/r}}\right|\right|_{r}^{r_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

where we've gotten rid of the minus sign by exchanging the limits of the
 evaluation.
 This works, because 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}>r$
\end_inset

 and so the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 coordinate is increasing as 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 decreases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Null radial geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted earlier, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}=\pm E/m=\mbox{const.}$
\end_inset

 also provides a solution.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

 in this case, this solution corresponds to null geodesics.
 Since the solutions to this equation are just arcs with constant arc velocity,
 one can set 
\begin_inset Formula $E/m=1$
\end_inset

 without any loss of generality.
 Integrating, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\left(\tau\right)=r_{f}\pm\left(\tau-\tau_{f}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for the radial coordinate.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{f},r_{f}\right)$
\end_inset

 are the flashlight coordinates, at the time that a flashlight emits it's
 signal.
 The proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the proper time of the flashlight (and is encoded in the flashlight
 transmission).
 With this offset, the arc parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 continues to measure from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 when the flashlight was dropped.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the time coordinate, proceed much as before, by flipping over the coordinate
s
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\tau}{dr}=\frac{dt}{dr}\frac{d\tau}{dt}=\pm1
\]

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dt}{dr}=\pm\dot{t}=\pm\frac{1}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}
\]

\end_inset

The integration proceeds as before, i.e.
 tediously:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\left(r\right)=\pm\int_{r_{f}}^{r}\frac{dr}{1-2m/r}
\]

\end_inset

Performing a change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2m/r$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2m/y$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $dr=-2mdy/y^{2}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int\frac{dr}{1-2m/r}= & -2m\int\frac{dy}{y^{2}\left(1-y\right)}\\
= & -2m\left[\int\frac{dy}{y^{2}}+\int\frac{dy}{y}+\int\frac{dy}{1-y}\right]\\
= & -2m\left[-\frac{1}{y}+\log y\mp_{EH}\log\left|1-y\right|\right]\\
= & 2m\left[\frac{r}{2m}+\log\frac{r}{2m}\pm_{EH}\log\left|1-\frac{2m}{r}\right|\right]\\
= & r\pm_{EH}2m\log\left|\frac{r}{2m}-1\right|
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm_{EH}$
\end_inset

 is a horizon-dependent sign: take the upper sign when 
\begin_inset Formula $2m<r$
\end_inset

 and the lower when 
\begin_inset Formula $2m>r$
\end_inset

.
 This is basically a cheap hack to allow us to continue working with interior
 solutions without having to go over to other coordinate systems (yet; we'll
 do this eventually).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 coordinate for null geodesics is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\left(r\right)=\pm\left.r\pm_{EH}2m\log\left|\frac{r}{2m}-1\right|\right|_{r_{f}}^{r}
\]

\end_inset

The first 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 uses the upper sign for outgoing geodesics, and the lower sign for infalling
 geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Thought experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the thought experiment as posed, there are only two relevant cases:
 the radially outgoing geodesics, emitted by some flashlight directly in
 front of the observer, and the radially ingoing geodesics, emitted by some
 flashlight directly behind the observer.
 Specifically, the goal here is to determine what the observer sees, to
 track the progress of these two geodesics to the observers eyes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, consider a signal transmitted at coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{f},r_{f}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 denotes the flashlight parameters (the flashlight's proper time and UUID.)
 The signal is to be received at the location 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{a},r_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

, with the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 denoting the astronaut.
 The signal encodes the flashlights proper time and UUID; we wish to determine
 what these are, when they are received.
 In addition, we'd like to know what the redshift is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since both the flashlights and the astronaut start falling at the same time,
 it is enough to use geodesic variation to obtain their relative positions.
 Initially, they are separated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\delta t_{0},\delta r_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 After both fall for an equal amount of proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, they end up separated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\delta t,\delta r\right)$
\end_inset

, at which point, the flashlight emits a signal.
 The astronaut continues to fall for an addtional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

 in proper time, before receiving the signal.
 What is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

? This can be computed by incrementing the proper time on the astronaut
 until the distance between flashlight and astronaut is zero.
 That is, we solve for the intersection point between the null geodesic
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{n},r_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and the astronaut 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{a},r_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{n},r_{n}\right)=\left(t_{a},r_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's try to put this all together.
 Just cut-n-paste the earlier formulas.
 Although it's quite the mess.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=\tau_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 as the infall begins all at the same time in the lab frame.
 The location of the forward flashlight is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta r_{0}<0$
\end_inset

 because it starts closer to the BH.
 After proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}$
\end_inset

, this flaslight is located at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r_{f}\left(\tau_{f}\right) & =\left[\left(r_{0}+\delta r_{0}\right)^{3/2}-\frac{3\sqrt{2m}}{2}\tau_{f}\right]^{2/3}\\
t_{f}\left(r_{f}\right) & =\left.\frac{2}{3}\left(r+6m\right)\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}+2m\log\left|\frac{1-\sqrt{2m/r}}{1+\sqrt{2m/r}}\right|\right|_{r_{f}}^{r_{0}+\delta r_{0}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The null geodesic propagates up, away from the BH, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r_{n}\left(\tau_{n}\right) & =r_{f}+\left(\tau_{n}-\tau_{f}\right)\\
t_{n}\left(r_{n}\right) & =t_{f}\left(r_{f}\right)+\left.r\pm_{EH}2m\log\left|\frac{r}{2m}-1\right|\right|_{r_{f}}^{r_{n}}\\
 & =t_{f}\left(r_{f}\right)+r_{n}-r_{f}\pm_{r_{n}}2m\log\left|\frac{r_{n}}{2m}-1\right|\pm_{r_{f}}2m\log\left|\frac{r_{f}}{2m}-1\right|
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which must equal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r_{a}\left(\tau_{a}\right) & =\left[r_{0}^{3/2}-\frac{3\sqrt{2m}}{2}\tau_{a}\right]^{2/3}\\
t_{a}\left(r_{a}\right) & =\left.\frac{2}{3}\left(r+6m\right)\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m}}+2m\log\left|\frac{1-\sqrt{2m/r}}{1+\sqrt{2m/r}}\right|\right|_{r_{a}}^{r_{0}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

One can immediately set 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}\left(\tau_{n}\right)=r_{a}\left(\tau_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 to eliminate the arc parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{n}$
\end_inset

 from further consideration.
 This leaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a}$
\end_inset

 as a free parameter.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a}$
\end_inset

 can be taken as the free parameter, and so one solves for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\left(r_{a}\right)=t_{a}\left(r_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This looks algebraically daunting, and needs to be solved numerically.
\end_layout

